{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640215"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:14:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:14:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17813"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17813"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.23,0,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73218"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10527"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17813"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58689"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9926"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24571"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24996"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73218"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe control of breathing requires coordination between multiple regions in the brainstem. The medulla oblongata contains specialised groups of neurons that form the respiratory centre.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary role of neurons in the medullary respiratory centre?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Generate respiratory rhythm and pattern","Detect blood carbon dioxide levels","Control airway smooth muscle tone","Monitor lung inflation pressure","Regulate bronchial secretions"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary role of neurons in the medullary respiratory centre is to \u003Cstrong\u003Egenerate respiratory rhythm and pattern\u003C/strong\u003E. This centre contains:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDorsal respiratory group - controls inspiration\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVentral respiratory group - controls expiration\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPre-B\u00f6tzinger complex - generates basic breathing rhythm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other respiratory control functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection of blood carbon dioxide levels\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by central chemoreceptors in the medulla and peripheral chemoreceptors in the carotid and aortic bodies. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControl of airway smooth muscle tone\u003C/strong\u003E is regulated by autonomic nervous system input. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung inflation pressure\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eis\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Emonitored\u003C/strong\u003E by stretch receptors in the airways and lung tissue. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulation of bronchial secretions\u003C/strong\u003E is controlled by autonomic innervation of submucosal glands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the medullary respiratory centre receives input from various sources including chemoreceptors and mechanoreceptors, its fundamental role is generating and maintaining the basic pattern of breathing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The medullary respiratory centre contains the dorsal respiratory group (inspiration) and ventral respiratory group (expiration).","The pre-B\u00f6tzinger complex within the medulla generates the basic rhythm of breathing.","The medullary respiratory centre receives modulatory input from chemoreceptors, mechanoreceptors and higher centres."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58689"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17813"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58689"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T09:14:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T09:15:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10527"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73218"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Leve